{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489422"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"657"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/657"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.19,0.31,0.07,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/657"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52825"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"448"},{"type":"tags","id":"904"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22566"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of acute abdominal pain, distension and absolute constipation. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a distended abdomen with an area of localised tenderness in the left lower quadrant. A plain abdominal radiograph shows the characteristic changes of a sigmoid volvulus (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most suspicious for infarction of the sigmoid volvulus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Persistence of severe colicky pain","Inability to decompress the colon with a flatus tube","An area of localised tenderness in the left lower quadrant","Asymmetric distension of the abdomen","A colon dilated more than 10 cm on the radiograph"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMost acute obstructive problems of the gut can be managed in the initial stages with a conservative approach. Usually, an acute episode of a volvulus of the sigmoid colon can be overcome by sigmoidoscopic or colonoscopic decompression. However, in the assessment of a patient with any type of intestinal obstruction, thought must be given to the need for any form of prompt intervention. If the obstruction is thought to be complicated by ischaemia or perforation, then continued conservative management is no longer appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn area of \u003Cstrong\u003Elocalised tenderness in the left lower quadrant\u003C/strong\u003E in an otherwise soft abdomen would suggest underlying peritoneal irritation - which might be secondary to inflammation and ischaemic changes in the adjacent sigmoid colon in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersistence of severe colicky pain\u003C/strong\u003E would be consistent with intestinal obstruction (which is present), but in itself, would not be suggestive of any ischaemic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einability to decompress the colon with a flatus tube\u003C/strong\u003E and a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolon dilated more than 10 cm on the radiograph\u003C/strong\u003E are worrying features that may indicate the need for surgical intervention, but are not as concerning for ischemia as localised peritonitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsymmetric distension of the abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E could indicate a particular area of the bowel (the volvulus) being distended, but is unrelated to any potential ischaemic event.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Localised tenderness identified on abdominal examination is very suggestive of an underlying peritonitis process."],"references":["Bauman ZM, Evans CH. Volvulus. Surg Clin N Am 2018; 98:973-93. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30243456/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52825"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"657"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21290"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21290"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Sw5gZkpBbTcGHiG7zUKlbs1y4ZmUxg.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Sw5gZkpBbTcGHiG7zUKlbs1y4ZmUxg.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":467,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52825"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T08:28:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T08:28:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"657"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67373"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"h